com.bigdata.bop.engine

Class BOpStats

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.bigdata.bop.engine.BOpStats
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Serializable
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    BaseJoinStats, NamedSolutionSetStats, ParserStats, SliceOp.SliceStats

    public class BOpStats
extends Object
implements Serializable
    Statistics associated with the evaluation of a BOp. These statistics are per BOp. The top-level BOp will reflect the throughput for the entire pipeline.

    • Field Detail

      • elapsed

        public final CAT elapsed
        The elapsed time (milliseconds) for the corresponding operation. When aggregated, this will generally exceed the wall time since concurrent processes are nearly always used during query evaluation.

      • opCount

        public final CAT opCount
        The #of instances of a given operator which have been started (and successully terminated) for a given query. This provides interesting information about the #of task instances for each operator which were required to execute a query.
        See Also:
        Explain reports incorrect value for opCount

      • typeErrors

        public final CAT typeErrors
        The #of error which were masked by the semantics of the query.

        Note: SPARQL type errors in aggregations often cause bindings or solutions to fail without causing any runtime exception which can be observed at the query level. This counter provides a means to observe those errors.

      • mutationCount

        public final CAT mutationCount
        The #of tuples written onto a relation (not an index).

        Note: This mutation counts should reflect the #of tuples written on a relation rather than on an index. The per-index tuple mutation count MAY also be reported, but it should be reported by extending this class and declaring additional mutation counters.

        Note: Operations which fix point some closure depend on the correctness of the mutationCount for their termination condition.

        Note: Mutation operations MUST NOT overwrite existing tuples with identical state. This is important for two reasons. First, fix point operations depend on the mutationCount being ZERO (0) in a given round if nothing was changed in order to terminate the closure. Second, due to the general MVCC and copy-on-write architecture, index writes drive IO. If the tuple state would not be changed, then the index write SHOULD NOT be performed.
